[1] The Netherlands: bovine tuberculosis ex UK
Date: Fri 18 Jul 2008
Source: The Herald [edited]
<http://www.theherald.co.uk/business/farming/display.var.2401815.0.Netherlands_ban_endangers_British_export_industry.php>


Netherlands ban endangers British export industry
-------------------------------------------------
A voluntary ban by Dutch cattle importers on the live export of cattle from
the UK threatens to devastate the British export industry, just as it was
recovering from last year's [2007] foot and mouth [disease] restrictions.

The move comes after 12 calves, which were exported from a farm in England
to 6 farms in the Netherlands had to be slaughtered after subsequent tests
on the English farm detected tuberculosis [TB] in the herd. A further 27
farms that have been in contact with the original 6 are now under
restriction and Dutch vets are testing more than 4000 cattle for the disease.

Unofficially, Belgian farmers are also refusing to take British calves and
adult cattle. Exporters fear that a complete ban on the trade of live
cattle throughout the European Union could be in force next week. The news
has shocked farmers in the Netherlands, which has been free of TB since 1994.

During 2006, the UK exported a total of 81 000 live calves. That figure
fell to 64 000 in 2007 as a result of export restrictions due to
foot-and-mouth disease, but was recovering well this year [2008] and latest
figures to June reveal that 40 000 had crossed the English Channel.

The next 3 months is the peak period when most UK calves are selected for
the export trade to the Netherlands, and any disruption to this trade will
result in the complete collapse of export businesses that have already lost
millions because of last year's [2007] foot and mouth disease ban.

NFU (National Farmers' Union) Scotland vice-president Nigel Miller said:
"This is a very worrying development at a time when Scotland's dairy
farmers are achieving BP 50 to BP 60 per head [USD 99.70 to 119.64] for
export-quality bull calves. "We have spoken to Scotland's chief vet to
raise our concerns while our Brussels office is in dialogue with their
Dutch union counterparts on the subject. If the Commission becomes
involved, then what we would want to see is a proportionate response to
this issue, one which takes the wider calf trade in the EU into
consideration and one which stops well short of a unilateral ban on live
calf exports from the UK.

"Scotland has worked hard to preserve its excellent record on TB. We
already have low incidence status and, as an industry, we have set targets
to further reduce the number of cases of TB seen here. Any suggestion of a
European ban on live calves affecting Scotland would be unjustified and
unnecessary."

[byline: Rog Wood]

