[2] UK (Wales): badger cull policy discussed
Date: Tue 15 Jul 2008
Source: Wales Online, Western Mail report [edited]
<http://www.walesonline.co.uk/countryside-farming-news/farming-news/2008/07/15/wales-will-kill-badgers-row-91466-21339761/>


Wales will kill badgers -- row
------------------------------
The DEFRA (UK Department for Environment, Food, and Rural Affairs)
secretary of state's decision to rule out a badger cull in England will not
affect proposals to go ahead with one in Wales.

Rural Affairs minister Elin Jones said nothing had changed and plans for a
cull in a pilot area as part of a package of measures to eradicate bTB
[bovine tuberculosis] were proceeding as announced last April [2008]. "It
has not affected my thinking at all. Various expert groups set up to advise
are gathering information as we speak on the various factors we need to
take account of," said Ms Jones. "Then at some point later in the year I
will be given advice from my officials as to what, when and where."

Among the issues that need to be addressed is the willingness of all
landowners to take part in the trial cull. This will only work if officials
are able to slaughter all the animals within a clearly defined area in
order to gauge whether it has any effect on the spread of the disease.

A small minority of farmers opposes a badger cull, and larger numbers of
landowners with small acreages may try to prevent it from happening. The
Badger Trust has already lodged an application for a judicial review of a
"naive and short-sighted political decision". The trust claims the badger
plays no role in the spread of bTB, which now affects more than 2000 farms
in Wales. Last year [2007] nearly 8000 cattle were culled at a cost in
compensation to farmers of BP 15.2m [USD 30.3m].

"The harsh reality is that Wales' bovine TB problem can be easily traced to
cattle movements and farming practices," says a Badger Trust report. "There
is a clear and known correlation between larger herd sizes and an increased
risk of bovine TB."

The National Farmers' Union has promised a legal challenge to what it calls
the UK environment minister Hilary Benn's "disgraceful abdication of
responsibility" in ruling out a cull. NFU president, Bedfordshire farmer
Peter Kendall and vice president Meurig Raymond, who farms in
Pembrokeshire, led a demonstration outside the House of Parliament after Mr
Benn's announcement. Mr Kendall said the NFU would mount a legal challenge
and withdraw from talks on cost and responsibility sharing. The Tenant
Farmers Association (TFA) has also pulled out of talks on sharing the costs
and responsibilities of animal diseases, which it describes as
"hypocritical and damaging" without controls of bTB in wildlife.

[byline: Steve Dube]

