[Additional information on the recent bovine tuberculosis developments in
England, which -- according to available science-based information -- is
directly related to the infection in badgers, can be found at
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/environment/article4340286.ece>.

DEFRA's explanatory information is available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/tb/index.htm>.

The number of new outbreaks in cattle during 2007, as reported to the OIE
(World Organisation for Animal Health), was: England -- 3153(!); Wales --
902; Scotland -- 58. Updated information on possible cases of human
_Mycobacterium bovis_ infections in the various parts of the UK would be
appreciated.

According to OIE's WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database)
interface data, bovine tuberculosis was present in the Netherlands during
2005 but no quantitative data were disclosed. Reportedly, the disease was
absent during the 1st half of 2006; no information is available for the 2nd
half of 2006 or for 2007.

OIE's WAHID data on new outbreaks in Belgium during the previous 2 years
are the following: 2006 -- 7; 2007 -- 5. From a reliable source we have
obtained the following unofficial information: "A farm in Belgium, just
across the German border, went down with TB last month [June 2008].
Allegedly, 22 cows out of 70 tested positive on the skin test."
Confirmation (or, it is to be hoped, denial) of the information above from
official sources would be appreciated. - Mod.AS]
